00:12:25.239 --> 00:12:26.719
So who am I?

00:12:26.719 --> 00:12:28.679
This is me.

00:12:28.679 --> 00:12:34.359
And I actually recently graduated with my master's degree.

00:12:34.359 --> 00:12:37.880
I did the whole full-time work and full-time school thing

00:12:37.880 --> 00:12:40.760
while I was doing my master's degree.

00:12:40.760 --> 00:12:46.599
As I was working at Posit, I was writing this Vetiver framework

00:12:46.599 --> 00:12:48.880
and finishing my degree.

00:12:48.880 --> 00:12:54.080
And part of what made me so excited about MLOps

00:12:54.080 --> 00:12:56.119
was because of what I had learned in my degree.

00:12:58.840 --> 00:13:01.000
And when I was learning about data science,

00:13:01.000 --> 00:13:06.119
my degree was in data science, half computer science,

00:13:06.119 --> 00:13:10.239
half data science, one of those weird in-between things.

00:13:10.239 --> 00:13:13.239
But I learned about a data science workflow

00:13:13.239 --> 00:13:14.679
that looked like this.

00:13:14.679 --> 00:13:16.479
You start with some data.

00:13:16.479 --> 00:13:19.960
You collect it, whether that's from an API or from CSVs

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:22.719
or people are just handing you data.

00:13:22.719 --> 00:13:24.640
You get this data.

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:29.000
And then you get to use some tools to understand the data.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:32.840
And that's things like the tidyverse or data table.

00:13:32.840 --> 00:13:35.599
If you are in the R world, I actually

00:13:35.599 --> 00:13:37.280
work in the Python space as well.

00:13:37.280 --> 00:13:40.559
So you're going to see some Python references.

00:13:40.559 --> 00:13:44.960
So I might use something like Pandas or NumPy or Suba

00:13:44.960 --> 00:13:50.799
if you guys are looking ever for a dplyr-like Python package.

00:13:50.799 --> 00:13:51.840
Suba is amazing.

00:13:54.760 --> 00:13:56.440
And so you have this data.

00:13:56.440 --> 00:13:57.159
You've cleaned it.

00:13:57.159 --> 00:13:58.559
You've understood it.

00:13:58.559 --> 00:14:00.919
And then in this data science workflow,

00:14:00.919 --> 00:14:05.080
you train and evaluate some sort of model.

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:09.840
That's using things like Carrot or tidymodels and R

00:14:09.840 --> 00:14:13.760
or Keras or scikit-learn or PyTorch and Python.

00:14:13.760 --> 00:14:18.440
Some of those are in both languages.

00:14:18.440 --> 00:14:21.520
And as I was learning all of these different data science

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:25.679
things, I was learning about best practices in data science.

00:14:25.679 --> 00:14:27.400
And I will give you guys a warning.

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:30.280
There is Python code on my slides.

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:33.520
This is not to scare anyone off.

00:14:33.520 --> 00:14:38.239
I personally am a Python person primarily.

00:14:38.239 --> 00:14:40.919
The end will be in R. But I just want

00:14:40.919 --> 00:14:42.679
to show you guys that these concepts are

00:14:42.679 --> 00:14:44.520
the same in both languages.

00:14:44.520 --> 00:14:48.119
And these frameworks actually exist in both languages.

00:14:48.119 --> 00:14:51.119
So you're going to get a dose of both.

00:14:51.119 --> 00:14:54.039
So some best practices in data science

00:14:54.039 --> 00:14:57.760
are things like setting your seed for reproducibility.

00:14:57.760 --> 00:15:00.640
If you've worked in different data science worlds,

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:02.200
this is the first thing you learn

00:15:02.200 --> 00:15:06.960
to do to make sure when you load data, it's always the same.

00:15:06.960 --> 00:15:09.520
Just good things for this reproducible data science

00:15:09.520 --> 00:15:10.840
workflow.

00:15:10.840 --> 00:15:13.119
And you also learn about best practices

00:15:13.119 --> 00:15:20.320
like splitting your data into test and training data sets.

00:15:20.320 --> 00:15:23.000
So you're not giving your model the answers

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:25.679
while you're training it.

00:15:25.679 --> 00:15:28.840
There's whole workbooks, whole textbooks

00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:33.000
on these best practices that we will not dive into today.

00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:37.239
But it's good to know these are very well-known things.

00:15:37.239 --> 00:15:39.239
Making sure you're choosing the right feature

00:15:39.239 --> 00:15:41.200
engineering for your model.

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:43.640
Making sure you're putting these things into a pipeline

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:46.239
if it's feature engineering that you're training.

00:15:46.239 --> 00:15:49.159
These are things that span across languages

00:15:49.159 --> 00:15:51.239
that you kind of always have to keep in mind

00:15:51.239 --> 00:15:54.479
as you are doing data science.

00:15:54.479 --> 00:15:57.799
But my first job as a data scientist

00:15:57.799 --> 00:16:01.039
before I was building software, the problems

00:16:01.039 --> 00:16:05.799
I encountered as a data scientist were different.

00:16:05.799 --> 00:16:07.599
I knew all of these best practices.

00:16:07.599 --> 00:16:11.039
But I realized the issues I was running into

00:16:11.039 --> 00:16:14.080
is how do you share data with your teammates?

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:19.880
Like, are you emailing everybody CSVs or Excel files?

00:16:19.880 --> 00:16:23.280
How are you sharing models with each other?

00:16:23.280 --> 00:16:24.559
Is it on Git?

00:16:24.559 --> 00:16:27.880
Is it, again, emailing things around?

00:16:27.880 --> 00:16:31.080
And how do you get people who don't code as much

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:34.520
to be able to engage with the things that you have created?

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:41.960
Oftentimes, at the end, you have a Shiny application

00:16:41.960 --> 00:16:44.159
that your model is running in.

00:16:44.159 --> 00:16:47.239
And how do you put that model into a Shiny application?

00:16:47.239 --> 00:16:49.479
There's a lot of different problems

00:16:49.479 --> 00:16:51.919
when you're putting this whole cycle of data science

00:16:51.919 --> 00:16:55.119
together that are just kind of beyond the best practices

00:16:55.119 --> 00:16:58.520
that I had learned in school.

00:16:58.520 --> 00:17:01.400
So a lot of these practices maybe weren't enough.

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:04.439
And I also learned that if you develop models,

00:17:04.439 --> 00:17:06.800
you can operationalize them.

00:17:06.800 --> 00:17:09.599
And so this is making sure that your models are

00:17:09.599 --> 00:17:14.439
in some sort of larger ecosystem.

00:17:14.439 --> 00:17:16.199
Maybe that's on Git.

00:17:16.199 --> 00:17:18.760
Maybe that's shared with your teammates in some way,

00:17:18.760 --> 00:17:24.640
making sure that the model isn't just on your computer.

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.439
So I learned that you want to bring your model

00:17:27.439 --> 00:17:29.599
outside your computer.

00:17:29.599 --> 00:17:31.760
And you want to learn kind of the best practices

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:34.479
of how to do that as well.

00:17:34.479 --> 00:17:38.280
And so those best practices for machine learning operations

00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:42.479
to operationalize your model are called MLOps.

00:17:42.479 --> 00:17:45.680
And so there's a lot of hype around this word

00:17:45.680 --> 00:17:47.319
that I find online.

00:17:47.319 --> 00:17:49.439
It's like, I don't even know what MLOps is.

00:17:49.439 --> 00:17:52.439
You can read all of these different startups.

00:17:52.439 --> 00:17:53.880
And you read their documentation.

00:17:53.880 --> 00:17:54.760
And you don't really know what they're

00:17:54.760 --> 00:17:55.959
doing at the end of it.

00:17:55.959 --> 00:17:57.920
It's kind of stressful to get started.

00:17:57.920 --> 00:18:00.719
But here is a kind of one-liner.

00:18:00.719 --> 00:18:04.239
MLOps is a set of practices to deploy and maintain

00:18:04.239 --> 00:18:06.599
machine learning models in production

00:18:06.599 --> 00:18:08.719
reliably and efficiently.

00:18:08.719 --> 00:18:13.000
So where we had those best practices like setting a seed

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:16.959
or splitting your training and testing data to build a model,

00:18:16.959 --> 00:18:20.479
MLOps are the same different set of practices.

00:18:20.479 --> 00:18:23.479
But it's a set of practices to make sure

00:18:23.479 --> 00:18:26.280
that the model, when it leaves your computer,

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:29.959
can still be reproducible and shared

00:18:29.959 --> 00:18:33.800
in a safe way with others.

00:18:33.800 --> 00:18:39.959
In my first job, when I was starting to learn about MLOps

00:18:39.959 --> 00:18:42.839
and learn how to deploy models, I

00:18:42.839 --> 00:18:46.880
was struggling because there was a set of tools that

00:18:46.880 --> 00:18:50.760
were really based on Kubernetes.

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:55.680
And it felt like I almost had to be like a cloud expert

00:18:55.680 --> 00:18:59.119
and then also like a DevOps expert

00:18:59.119 --> 00:19:02.040
and maybe kind of a systems architect and also a data

00:19:02.040 --> 00:19:02.680
scientist.

00:19:02.680 --> 00:19:05.680
And that felt like way too much.

00:19:05.680 --> 00:19:07.760
These practices are hard.

00:19:07.760 --> 00:19:13.640
It gets models off your computer into some sort of larger system.

00:19:13.640 --> 00:19:16.439
And sometimes tools don't necessarily

00:19:16.439 --> 00:19:20.439
feel ergonomic for data scientists.

00:19:20.439 --> 00:19:23.239
It felt like these tools were not really

00:19:23.239 --> 00:19:25.040
made for people with the skill set

00:19:25.040 --> 00:19:29.880
that I had coming from a purely data science background.

00:19:29.880 --> 00:19:34.239
And that is kind of how Bediver was created.

00:19:34.239 --> 00:19:37.439
I ended up changing career paths from doing data science

00:19:37.439 --> 00:19:43.239
to building data science tools and making these MLOps tools

00:19:43.239 --> 00:19:48.680
to feel like an extension of what people are already doing.

00:19:48.680 --> 00:19:51.839
So I do work for Posit, the company that was formerly

00:19:51.839 --> 00:19:53.079
known as RStudio.

00:19:53.079 --> 00:19:56.079
Bediver is funded by Posit because I'm

00:19:56.079 --> 00:19:58.040
an affiliate for them.

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:01.760
So it's no surprise that while I'm showing you Python code

00:20:01.760 --> 00:20:04.319
and while I primarily write in Python,

00:20:04.319 --> 00:20:07.319
there is also an R version of Bediver as well.

00:20:07.319 --> 00:20:10.319
The code actually looks almost identical.

00:20:10.319 --> 00:20:13.040
And that was on purpose, especially

00:20:13.040 --> 00:20:14.920
realizing that people sometimes might

00:20:14.920 --> 00:20:16.920
have to work in different languages

00:20:16.920 --> 00:20:21.280
or collaborate with people who are using different languages.

00:20:21.280 --> 00:20:24.079
We wanted to make tools that feel super easy to go back

00:20:24.079 --> 00:20:25.839
and forth so it doesn't feel like you

00:20:25.839 --> 00:20:28.400
have to start from zero if you're

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:31.760
moving between languages.

00:20:31.760 --> 00:20:33.959
So part of the idea of Bediver is

00:20:33.959 --> 00:20:36.680
that there's this life cycle where

00:20:36.680 --> 00:20:41.800
you collect and understand and evaluate your model.

00:20:41.800 --> 00:20:44.319
But it wants to fill in the gap of how

00:20:44.319 --> 00:20:47.199
to get this model out into the real world,

00:20:47.199 --> 00:20:50.880
making predictions from real world data

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:53.560
in a really safe, reproducible way.

00:20:56.839 --> 00:20:58.880
So some of the tasks that Bediver helps with,

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:01.000
actually, I'm going to go back to this

00:21:01.000 --> 00:21:03.520
because I like this slide better,

00:21:03.520 --> 00:21:07.719
is to version your models, to deploy your models,

00:21:07.719 --> 00:21:10.160
and to monitor your models.

00:21:10.160 --> 00:21:13.040
And those are the three main tasks Bediver focuses on.

00:21:13.040 --> 00:21:17.599
There are many, many other best practices

00:21:17.599 --> 00:21:21.199
that envelops in cases.

00:21:21.199 --> 00:21:24.359
But we really wanted to narrow down what, when I say we,

00:21:24.359 --> 00:21:26.880
it's me and the Bediver team, wanted

00:21:26.880 --> 00:21:31.359
to narrow down what we thought was important for people who

00:21:31.359 --> 00:21:33.640
are just starting to deploy models, who are just

00:21:33.640 --> 00:21:35.880
trying to figure out what this world is

00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:37.000
and what it means for them.

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:42.239
So the first step of this is versioning.

00:21:42.239 --> 00:21:45.119
And when people think of versioning,

00:21:45.119 --> 00:21:47.560
it's normally in the context of Git,

00:21:47.560 --> 00:21:52.839
where you have some sort of central repository of files

00:21:52.839 --> 00:21:58.280
that people can read and write to, like push and pull to.

00:21:58.280 --> 00:22:00.199
But people actually version a lot of things.

00:22:00.199 --> 00:22:06.319
And they normally version things pretty badly, actually.

00:22:06.319 --> 00:22:11.599
I think of how I am building models in my past.

00:22:11.599 --> 00:22:12.520
And I would version.

00:22:12.520 --> 00:22:13.640
I would start with a model.

00:22:13.640 --> 00:22:18.959
And I save it probably as a RDS file or as a Joblib file.

00:22:18.959 --> 00:22:20.359
So I save my model.

00:22:20.359 --> 00:22:23.479
I name it model, or maybe something a little better.

00:22:23.479 --> 00:22:27.119
And then maybe you update some of your features

00:22:27.119 --> 00:22:28.880
when you get new data.

00:22:28.880 --> 00:22:30.880
Then you re-save it, and it's model final.

00:22:30.880 --> 00:22:33.680
And then maybe you realize that it

00:22:33.680 --> 00:22:35.719
needs a little bit more tweaking.

00:22:35.719 --> 00:22:37.680
And so you have your model vinyl final.

00:22:37.680 --> 00:22:39.680
And you guys see where this goes.

00:22:39.680 --> 00:22:45.560
You end up with all of these versions of one object

00:22:45.599 --> 00:22:51.160
that maybe you need information from multiple files of these.

00:22:51.160 --> 00:22:53.800
But it's not really scalable.

00:22:53.800 --> 00:22:55.439
And these aren't really reproducible.

00:22:55.439 --> 00:22:57.719
And it doesn't really make much sense,

00:22:57.719 --> 00:22:59.680
because then you have to remember which is which

00:22:59.680 --> 00:23:01.880
and all of its other information.

00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:06.000
Versioning really is the foundation for success

00:23:06.000 --> 00:23:08.359
in machine learning deployments.

00:23:08.359 --> 00:23:11.040
And also maybe not just for machine learning deployments,

00:23:11.040 --> 00:23:14.560
but a lot of reproducibility problems.

00:23:14.560 --> 00:23:18.800
A well-versioned system, a well-versioned file

00:23:18.800 --> 00:23:22.280
is normally going to be easier to share.

00:23:22.280 --> 00:23:25.439
It's going to be easier for you to share with yourself

00:23:25.439 --> 00:23:28.760
six months from now as well.

00:23:28.760 --> 00:23:31.680
So when we think about our ideal versioning system,

00:23:31.680 --> 00:23:33.640
it would be nice if all of these files

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:36.239
kind of lived in a central location

00:23:36.239 --> 00:23:40.400
so you don't have to search between different directories,

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:43.400
maybe if they were discoverable by a team,

00:23:43.439 --> 00:23:46.599
so something that's not just on your computer,

00:23:46.599 --> 00:23:49.560
but something that can be hosted in a cloud environment

00:23:49.560 --> 00:23:51.280
between people.

00:23:51.280 --> 00:23:53.239
And it's also really nice

00:23:53.239 --> 00:23:55.520
if things can be loaded right into memory

00:23:55.520 --> 00:23:59.040
so you don't have to, like,

00:23:59.040 --> 00:24:01.760
the problem I have with Git sometimes with data

00:24:01.760 --> 00:24:04.000
is you'll have to go download the data

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.160
if you can't in an easy way,

00:24:07.160 --> 00:24:09.439
load it onto your local computer,

00:24:09.439 --> 00:24:12.560
open up RStudio, load the data in that.

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:16.680
So it's a few extra steps.

00:24:16.680 --> 00:24:19.199
And sometimes Git is difficult for people

00:24:19.199 --> 00:24:21.760
who don't have that skill set

00:24:21.760 --> 00:24:23.319
or maybe that's not their primary job

00:24:23.319 --> 00:24:26.400
is to be working in these version control systems.

00:24:26.400 --> 00:24:29.079
So something that helps Venifer out

00:24:29.079 --> 00:24:32.920
is actually another package called Pins.

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:35.920
And we're going to do, like, a very small Pins side quest.

00:24:35.920 --> 00:24:39.880
You don't actually have to install Pins to use Venifer,

00:24:39.880 --> 00:24:42.280
but they play together really nicely

00:24:42.280 --> 00:24:46.040
and they're kind of built alongside each other.

00:24:46.040 --> 00:24:48.640
And Pins is...

00:24:48.640 --> 00:24:50.479
Ooh.

00:24:50.479 --> 00:24:53.239
Oh, I'm missing a slide, but that's okay.

00:24:53.239 --> 00:24:57.239
So Pins is a package that publishes data,

00:24:57.239 --> 00:24:59.520
models, other R objects,

00:24:59.520 --> 00:25:01.439
and it makes it easy to share them

00:25:01.439 --> 00:25:07.199
between projects and with your colleagues.

00:25:07.199 --> 00:25:10.239
Some things that might be considered good uses for Pins

00:25:10.239 --> 00:25:16.040
are, like, an ETL pipeline that will store a model

00:25:16.040 --> 00:25:20.599
or summarize data sets maybe once a day.

00:25:20.599 --> 00:25:27.000
Pins, though, is not meant for multiple writing things

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:28.520
back and forth.

00:25:28.520 --> 00:25:31.319
Let me really quick...

00:25:31.319 --> 00:25:33.119
I don't know if you guys have ever done this.

00:25:33.119 --> 00:25:35.760
Speaking of versioning, I updated my slides locally

00:25:35.760 --> 00:25:37.719
and have not pushed them yet.

00:25:37.719 --> 00:25:41.000
So I'm going to very quickly swap

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:43.400
so you guys can get a slightly prettier version

00:25:43.400 --> 00:25:45.800
of what these are.

00:25:45.800 --> 00:25:55.160
I'm going to open this up.

00:25:55.160 --> 00:25:56.760
Sorry, please hold.

