00:26:42.000 --> 00:26:44.640
Okay.

00:26:44.640 --> 00:26:47.400
So it can be pinned in a variety of locations.

00:26:47.400 --> 00:26:49.439
Pins, we can pin models,

00:26:49.439 --> 00:26:52.199
but we can also pin other things like data.

00:26:52.199 --> 00:26:54.760
So if you have things as a CSV

00:26:54.760 --> 00:26:58.560
or as something in like an arrow format,

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:00.880
you can pin actual full files.

00:27:00.880 --> 00:27:05.680
I know people who pin entire packages, actually,

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:11.079
and anything that's an RDS object, you're able to pin.

00:27:11.079 --> 00:27:13.719
So what's actually super useful about pins,

00:27:13.719 --> 00:27:17.800
this is kind of a side quest,

00:27:17.800 --> 00:27:23.640
is that it actually is meant to go across languages as well.

00:27:23.640 --> 00:27:25.959
So if you are pinning something that can be loaded

00:27:25.959 --> 00:27:28.319
in R and Python,

00:27:28.319 --> 00:27:30.640
I collaborate with my teammates all the time.

00:27:30.640 --> 00:27:32.680
I'll pin up data in R

00:27:32.680 --> 00:27:35.040
because it's a lot easier to clean data in R,

00:27:35.040 --> 00:27:36.599
and then I'll read it into Python

00:27:36.599 --> 00:27:41.359
and use that exact same data set

00:27:41.359 --> 00:27:43.359
that I have just updated in R,

00:27:43.359 --> 00:27:46.199
pull it into Python for machine learning

00:27:46.199 --> 00:27:47.800
or something like that.

00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:56.280
So it's good for pipelines where things is read and or updated.

00:27:56.280 --> 00:28:02.079
Pins is not really meant to have multiple people

00:28:02.079 --> 00:28:04.079
writing data to it at once.

00:28:04.079 --> 00:28:07.479
You can have as many people as you want reading from it,

00:28:07.479 --> 00:28:09.800
but you can't have multiple writes.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:11.920
That is kind of a downside of pins.

00:28:11.920 --> 00:28:14.199
One thing that we see people try to do,

00:28:14.199 --> 00:28:16.239
and then I just kind of want to get ahead of,

00:28:16.239 --> 00:28:20.439
is don't try to make like a Google form with a pin.

00:28:20.439 --> 00:28:22.760
These are just files.

00:28:22.760 --> 00:28:24.680
So if you're trying to have multiple people

00:28:24.680 --> 00:28:26.119
like update the same file at once,

00:28:26.119 --> 00:28:27.560
it might get corrupt.

00:28:27.560 --> 00:28:31.800
But if one person or if, say, some sort of system

00:28:31.800 --> 00:28:35.839
is reading and writing this pin one at a time

00:28:35.839 --> 00:28:39.199
or you want to share something for multiple people to ingest,

00:28:39.199 --> 00:28:40.680
pins is good.

00:28:40.680 --> 00:28:43.000
Please don't make a Google format of it.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:44.599
I can tell you right now,

00:28:44.599 --> 00:28:48.920
I've had some horror stories from that.

00:28:48.920 --> 00:28:51.599
But what works really well is people have like GitHub

00:28:51.599 --> 00:28:54.199
Actions running where it will update a notebook

00:28:54.199 --> 00:28:55.599
or something like that,

00:28:55.599 --> 00:28:59.760
and pins is kind of a perfect solution for them.

00:28:59.760 --> 00:29:02.680
And pins is built to be like super easy to use.

00:29:02.680 --> 00:29:05.920
This is what it looks like in Python.

00:29:05.920 --> 00:29:14.199
In R, it's essentially just model board equals word temp.

00:29:14.199 --> 00:29:17.479
So this is what you would do if you wanted to make a board

00:29:17.479 --> 00:29:19.599
that goes directly on your computer.

00:29:19.599 --> 00:29:23.439
Pins works off this mental model where imagine you create

00:29:23.439 --> 00:29:25.560
like kind of like a pin board.

00:29:25.560 --> 00:29:28.959
I kind of have one right here on my wall

00:29:28.959 --> 00:29:31.800
where it's a collecting spot for a lot of different information.

00:29:31.800 --> 00:29:34.959
So you make a board and you pin different objects to it.

00:29:37.439 --> 00:29:40.800
For this, it'll be something that doesn't last on my computer,

00:29:40.800 --> 00:29:42.520
but it's good for like demo purposes

00:29:42.520 --> 00:29:45.040
or if you're just trying stuff out.

00:29:45.040 --> 00:29:47.599
This is a Python specific thing I won't dig into.

00:29:47.599 --> 00:29:50.359
If you're interested in what a pickle file is in Python,

00:29:50.359 --> 00:29:52.439
I'm happy to discuss.

00:29:56.680 --> 00:29:58.479
So this is the temporary board.

00:29:58.479 --> 00:30:02.680
If you want to change it to be a S3 board,

00:30:02.680 --> 00:30:05.359
it would just be board underscore S3

00:30:05.359 --> 00:30:08.319
or board underscore Azure, whatever.

00:30:08.319 --> 00:30:10.680
So it's super easy to like switch between boards

00:30:10.680 --> 00:30:13.199
or something like that.

00:30:13.199 --> 00:30:15.079
And this is where Vediver comes in.

00:30:15.079 --> 00:30:19.680
So let's say we are in our data science workflow.

00:30:19.680 --> 00:30:22.719
We have created our model.

00:30:22.719 --> 00:30:24.439
It's called RFPipe.

00:30:24.439 --> 00:30:28.160
This is like a random forest pipeline that I created.

00:30:28.160 --> 00:30:30.239
And we're ready to deploy it.

00:30:30.239 --> 00:30:33.319
So we want to create this deployable model object

00:30:33.319 --> 00:30:35.239
called a Vediver model.

00:30:35.239 --> 00:30:37.640
And our inputs into this Vediver model

00:30:37.640 --> 00:30:41.640
are going to be the model itself that we've created.

00:30:41.640 --> 00:30:44.199
And then we're going to give it a name as well.

00:30:44.199 --> 00:30:49.160
And the things that are useful about using this Vediver model

00:30:49.160 --> 00:30:55.280
object is that it holds onto a lot of information for you.

00:30:55.280 --> 00:30:56.599
Inside this Vediver model, you're

00:30:56.599 --> 00:30:59.800
going to have things like an input data prototype.

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:03.520
So when you created your model, you, of course,

00:31:03.520 --> 00:31:05.800
fed it some input data.

00:31:05.800 --> 00:31:10.119
And Vediver actually can like slurp that up on its own.

00:31:10.119 --> 00:31:13.719
And it knows the data that it should expect as an input.

00:31:13.719 --> 00:31:18.199
So if you have five columns and you accidentally

00:31:18.199 --> 00:31:20.479
put four when you're making a prediction,

00:31:20.479 --> 00:31:23.599
Vediver will tell you, like, no, that's wrong.

00:31:23.599 --> 00:31:26.199
Your data should be five columns,

00:31:26.199 --> 00:31:30.479
or if it has like a wrong date format or something like that.

00:31:30.479 --> 00:31:32.479
This becomes super useful when your model

00:31:32.479 --> 00:31:35.079
is deployed somewhere that's not on your computer.

00:31:38.079 --> 00:31:40.280
It also will say things like what packages

00:31:40.280 --> 00:31:43.400
are needed to recreate this model and a little bit of metadata

00:31:43.400 --> 00:31:44.439
about the model itself.

00:31:45.439 --> 00:31:49.000
And then with your model board and then your Vediver model

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:55.640
created, you can do a function that's just Vediver pin right,

00:31:55.640 --> 00:31:58.959
your model board, your Vediver model.

00:31:58.959 --> 00:32:02.800
And it will actually version your model automatically.

00:32:02.800 --> 00:32:07.520
So this will be wherever you want to place it.

00:32:07.520 --> 00:32:11.680
And your board will collect this information,

00:32:11.680 --> 00:32:15.800
will collect this information, collect this Vediver model,

00:32:15.800 --> 00:32:18.599
and kind of there it is.

00:32:18.599 --> 00:32:21.239
This is meant to be only a few lines of code.

00:32:21.239 --> 00:32:24.400
There's a little bit of magic that happens under the surface.

00:32:24.400 --> 00:32:27.040
But it's supposed to be kind of like a natural extension of what

00:32:27.040 --> 00:32:29.880
people are already doing.

00:32:29.880 --> 00:32:33.760
If you wanted to see the metadata that it saves,

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:37.920
you can see it has the title, it has a description,

00:32:37.920 --> 00:32:44.000
when the model was created, a hash, a little bit more robust versioning

00:32:44.000 --> 00:32:47.880
system than a bunch of underscore finals,

00:32:47.880 --> 00:32:52.000
as well as the required packages this used Vediver and Scikit-learn.

00:32:57.400 --> 00:33:00.000
There's other things that are beyond just creating

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:03.560
these models in Vediver.

00:33:03.599 --> 00:33:12.239
MLOps is not just about creating models that are in different locations.

00:33:12.239 --> 00:33:14.160
It's a lot about documenting and making sure

00:33:14.160 --> 00:33:18.479
you have good models that are well-documented, that are reproducible,

00:33:18.479 --> 00:33:23.680
and can really show what you've learned when you've created this model.

00:33:23.680 --> 00:33:26.560
We believe that when you've created the model,

00:33:26.560 --> 00:33:30.000
this is the time where you've spent all of your research.

00:33:30.000 --> 00:33:32.640
And there's no better person to write information about this model

00:33:32.640 --> 00:33:36.119
than the person who created it.

00:33:36.119 --> 00:33:43.760
So there are a few templates that you can pull up in RStudio.

00:33:43.760 --> 00:33:45.760
One of them is a model card.

00:33:45.760 --> 00:33:47.959
Actually, when you write the model itself,

00:33:47.959 --> 00:33:51.560
you'll get a little feedback that the model card is

00:33:51.560 --> 00:33:54.560
a framework for transparent, responsible reporting,

00:33:54.560 --> 00:33:59.160
and to use this Cordo framework as a place to start.

00:33:59.160 --> 00:34:05.079
And when you run this code in Python or use the template in RStudio,

00:34:05.079 --> 00:34:07.640
it gives you something that you can give your pin,

00:34:07.640 --> 00:34:13.159
and it will automatically document what it is able to automatically document.

00:34:13.159 --> 00:34:18.560
And then it has fill-in-the-blank type responses for things

00:34:18.560 --> 00:34:20.760
that a machine can't do.

00:34:20.760 --> 00:34:25.120
And that is knowledge that only the model developer would have.

00:34:25.120 --> 00:34:28.800
So you can see it has the model details,

00:34:28.800 --> 00:34:31.840
where you'd have to add your name.

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:35.080
But then it's a place, you know, there's four features,

00:34:35.080 --> 00:34:40.959
this is what was created, that the vet-over-framework will do for you.

00:34:40.959 --> 00:34:44.479
It'll also have what your model should expect,

00:34:44.479 --> 00:34:49.919
and a few different plots and analysis on your model.

00:34:49.919 --> 00:34:51.800
At the bottom, there's also some places for you

00:34:51.800 --> 00:34:56.879
to put ethical considerations and caveats and recommendations,

00:34:56.879 --> 00:34:59.080
which we believe, you know, even if you don't think

00:34:59.080 --> 00:35:01.959
that your model has any ethical considerations,

00:35:01.959 --> 00:35:06.399
that you should at least maybe put none that you know of,

00:35:06.399 --> 00:35:11.120
and to not just delete the section.

00:35:11.120 --> 00:35:16.080
Just if you don't have complete information,

00:35:16.080 --> 00:35:19.360
it's better to leave something blank to show that you've thought about it

00:35:19.360 --> 00:35:23.280
than to delete something altogether.

00:35:23.280 --> 00:35:26.560
And so with all of that information, with using pins,

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:30.879
you can version your model.

00:35:30.879 --> 00:35:35.879
And it's kind of the first step in this process of MLOps.

00:35:35.879 --> 00:35:38.280
So you think about saving your model into location,

00:35:38.280 --> 00:35:43.280
it has a robust version, it has metadata, it's shareable,

00:35:43.280 --> 00:35:51.639
it's not just a file system of you overriding your information.

00:35:51.639 --> 00:35:56.520
So next, we'll go on to deploying your model.

00:35:56.520 --> 00:36:00.840
So you have your model kind of saved in a central location.

00:36:00.840 --> 00:36:03.120
And at this point, if people want to use it,

00:36:03.120 --> 00:36:05.919
they have to go to that location, download it,

00:36:05.919 --> 00:36:11.439
run it in their environment, and kind of hope it works.

00:36:11.439 --> 00:36:15.000
Sometimes things work better on somebody's computer.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.639
Sometimes it's difficult to reproduce exact environments.

00:36:18.639 --> 00:36:22.840
You have to make sure you have all the exact same versions of packages,

00:36:22.840 --> 00:36:25.239
versions of R.

00:36:25.239 --> 00:36:28.239
So we think kind of the ideal scenario here

00:36:28.239 --> 00:36:31.639
is maybe your model is running somewhere

00:36:31.639 --> 00:36:35.479
that people can use it without even having to download it.

00:36:35.479 --> 00:36:37.840
And that is essentially what deploying your model means.

00:36:41.320 --> 00:36:43.280
So deploying your model, you're going

00:36:43.280 --> 00:36:46.399
to be moving your model here into someplace

00:36:46.399 --> 00:36:49.439
that is not your computer.

00:36:49.439 --> 00:36:52.439
It's super useful because others can use this model

00:36:52.439 --> 00:36:53.919
without having to load it.

00:36:53.919 --> 00:36:55.520
The way that we're going to create this

00:36:55.520 --> 00:37:00.159
is by using a REST API endpoint.

00:37:00.159 --> 00:37:05.520
An API is kind of a, I think it's application something process

00:37:05.520 --> 00:37:07.040
interface.

00:37:07.040 --> 00:37:14.199
Essentially, it is a place where people can ingest your model's

00:37:14.199 --> 00:37:15.840
information.

00:37:15.840 --> 00:37:17.479
The really nice thing about this is

00:37:17.479 --> 00:37:22.280
that it works with JSON, not necessarily R or Python,

00:37:22.280 --> 00:37:24.560
to send requests to and from your model.

00:37:24.560 --> 00:37:27.360
So it is pretty language agnostic,

00:37:27.360 --> 00:37:31.320
as long as the input data information is the same.

00:37:31.320 --> 00:37:39.360
So in Python and in R, it is pretty much one-ish lines of code

00:37:39.360 --> 00:37:43.120
to create a local API endpoint.

00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:50.879
In Python, it's putting this vetiver model v into a vetiver API

00:37:50.879 --> 00:37:53.719
and then calling run on it.

00:37:53.719 --> 00:37:57.639
In R, it is also creating a vetiver API

00:37:57.639 --> 00:37:59.560
that you're putting a vetiver model into

00:37:59.560 --> 00:38:03.560
and running it using Plumber, if you're familiar with Plumber,

00:38:03.560 --> 00:38:06.919
to make API endpoints.

00:38:06.919 --> 00:38:10.320
So this is going to give you a local API running.

00:38:10.320 --> 00:38:14.879
But of course, what we had wanted

00:38:14.879 --> 00:38:17.679
was a model that was not running on our computer.

00:38:17.679 --> 00:38:20.360
We want it to be shared somewhere else.

00:38:20.360 --> 00:38:23.760
So we have a one-liner for Posit Connect,

00:38:23.760 --> 00:38:26.239
which is one of Posit's pro products,

00:38:26.239 --> 00:38:28.439
where if you give it the board and the pin name

00:38:28.439 --> 00:38:30.439
and the version, it'll automatically

00:38:30.439 --> 00:38:33.719
deploy it as an API endpoint.

00:38:33.719 --> 00:38:36.439
But there's also ways to do this for Dockerfiles.

00:38:36.439 --> 00:38:39.959
So if you're working for a company that maybe is using

00:38:39.959 --> 00:38:42.000
a different cloud platform, most of them

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:46.360
have a bring your own container ideology.

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:51.159
So as long as you have some sort of Dockerfile,

00:38:51.159 --> 00:38:54.360
it will kind of automatically slip it up.

00:38:54.360 --> 00:38:57.080
It knows how to handle these Dockerfiles

00:38:57.080 --> 00:38:59.600
in these Docker containers.

00:38:59.600 --> 00:39:05.439
So this prepare Docker call for Python or R

00:39:05.439 --> 00:39:09.120
will create really three files for you.

00:39:09.120 --> 00:39:11.679
And these three files are what you'll

00:39:11.679 --> 00:39:15.919
need to deploy your Docker image locally or on another cloud.

00:39:16.439 --> 00:39:19.360
And that's the application file itself,

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:24.399
so kind of a plumber.r file, the Dockerfile,

00:39:24.399 --> 00:39:28.360
to give the system information on how to build the Docker image

00:39:28.360 --> 00:39:32.959
and a requirements.txt in Python or an rnlock file.

00:39:32.959 --> 00:39:36.840
So the computer that you're running this new API on

00:39:36.840 --> 00:39:38.760
will know all the information it needs

00:39:38.760 --> 00:39:45.080
to download the right packages and make sure

00:39:45.080 --> 00:39:47.360
it's all of the correct versions as well

00:39:47.360 --> 00:39:51.159
to ensure reproducibility.

00:39:51.159 --> 00:39:56.439
And with this image, this Docker image, this API endpoint up

00:39:56.439 --> 00:39:59.120
and running, you're able to just call predict.

00:39:59.120 --> 00:40:04.679
So predict with the data that you are running,

00:40:04.679 --> 00:40:06.159
that your model expects.

00:40:06.159 --> 00:40:08.399
So that can actually make predictions

00:40:08.399 --> 00:40:12.040
from this model locally, even if the model itself is not

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:13.040
running on your laptop.

00:40:16.080 --> 00:40:18.080
So that's what deploying a model looks like.

00:40:18.080 --> 00:40:22.520
I think kind of maybe the most famous deployed model right now

00:40:22.520 --> 00:40:24.159
would be something like chat-gpt,

00:40:24.159 --> 00:40:29.719
where you'll interact with it locally on your laptop.

00:40:29.719 --> 00:40:33.199
But the model, of course, is running somewhere else

00:40:33.199 --> 00:40:35.320
with all this information.

00:40:35.320 --> 00:40:37.719
But you don't have to be someone who

00:40:37.719 --> 00:40:40.760
knows how to run chat-gpt on your computer.

00:40:40.760 --> 00:40:43.360
All you have to do is interact with it.

00:40:43.360 --> 00:40:45.560
Which I think is really showcasing

00:40:45.560 --> 00:40:47.840
the beauty of MLOps and what a deployed model should

00:40:47.840 --> 00:40:52.520
look like and kind of how that should feel.

00:40:55.520 --> 00:40:57.399
I think it's a great thing.

00:40:57.399 --> 00:41:00.159
So the last piece of this is monitoring a model.

00:41:02.560 --> 00:41:05.159
So when you've created a model, you

00:41:05.159 --> 00:41:08.040
have your fresh data that looks great.

00:41:08.040 --> 00:41:09.399
It's performing well.

00:41:09.439 --> 00:41:11.800
But that is at the exact point in time

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:13.840
when the model is created.

00:41:13.840 --> 00:41:16.399
Oftentimes, data will change over time.

00:41:16.399 --> 00:41:23.040
I think of maybe my Spotify or whatever music listening

00:41:23.040 --> 00:41:25.239
platform I use.

00:41:25.239 --> 00:41:29.639
My music taste is different now than it was five years ago

00:41:29.639 --> 00:41:31.239
or 10 years ago.

00:41:31.239 --> 00:41:33.639
So models have to continually update,

00:41:33.639 --> 00:41:35.840
train if I got the same suggestion,

00:41:36.040 --> 00:41:38.840
I would probably not be on that platform anymore.

00:41:38.840 --> 00:41:41.040
So the same concept applies here.

00:41:41.040 --> 00:41:45.840
Models will often degrade over time.

00:41:45.840 --> 00:41:46.840
Not all the time.

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:52.840
But monitoring for MLOps might mean something different

00:41:52.840 --> 00:41:57.840
if you are a data scientist or if you are a data scientist

00:41:57.840 --> 00:41:59.639
and you're trying to figure out what

00:41:59.639 --> 00:42:05.000
might mean something different if you are a data scientist

00:42:05.000 --> 00:42:09.439
or if you are a systems admin.

00:42:09.439 --> 00:42:11.679
So what the Vennover framework looks

00:42:11.679 --> 00:42:15.959
like for MLOps monitoring is the statistical output

00:42:15.959 --> 00:42:17.280
of the model.

00:42:17.280 --> 00:42:20.639
So it's tracking things like maybe accuracy or R

00:42:20.639 --> 00:42:22.840
squared of a model, where a systems

00:42:22.840 --> 00:42:25.080
admin or a DevOps person, when they

00:42:25.080 --> 00:42:27.479
think that they're monitoring a model,

00:42:27.479 --> 00:42:31.199
they might be thinking about the CPU usage of a model

00:42:31.199 --> 00:42:33.879
or the runtime.

00:42:33.879 --> 00:42:35.320
So I think if you're collaborating

00:42:35.320 --> 00:42:36.760
with other teams, these are things

00:42:36.760 --> 00:42:40.760
to keep in mind that you're clear in your expectations

00:42:40.760 --> 00:42:43.399
of what these kind of loaded terms might mean,

00:42:43.399 --> 00:42:46.760
like monitoring.

00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:48.159
In the Vennover framework, there's

00:42:48.159 --> 00:42:52.239
really three main functions to kind of help people

00:42:52.239 --> 00:42:55.040
on their monitoring journey.

00:42:55.040 --> 00:42:58.760
It's to compute the metrics, where you give it the data,

00:42:58.760 --> 00:43:02.199
the column that has the date, the time

00:43:02.199 --> 00:43:03.639
that you want to aggregate over.

00:43:03.639 --> 00:43:06.639
So if you want to look at how your model has performed

00:43:06.639 --> 00:43:14.159
over every one week or one year, the metrics

00:43:14.159 --> 00:43:16.159
that you're trying to compute.

00:43:16.159 --> 00:43:18.879
So things like mean absolute error, R squared,

00:43:18.879 --> 00:43:26.000
and then the true value of the model, so the model

00:43:26.000 --> 00:43:29.120
output and the true value.

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:31.239
You can also do things like pin your metrics

00:43:31.239 --> 00:43:33.840
if you want to continue this information over time,

00:43:33.840 --> 00:43:38.520
if you want to write a small script to check this

00:43:38.520 --> 00:43:42.360
as you have different information come in,

00:43:42.360 --> 00:43:45.800
and then to plot the metrics themselves.

00:43:45.800 --> 00:43:50.000
There's also another, just like the model card,

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:52.760
there's another template in RStudio

00:43:52.760 --> 00:43:56.239
to build a monitoring dashboard if maybe your company

00:43:56.239 --> 00:43:58.479
or your team is someone who needs

00:43:58.479 --> 00:44:00.120
to monitor these models over time

00:44:00.120 --> 00:44:05.639
and wants a dashboard deployed to help look at that.

00:44:05.639 --> 00:44:10.600
So monitoring is extra important because models

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:14.560
don't fail loudly.

00:44:14.560 --> 00:44:17.919
So if you're thinking about building a Shiny app,

00:44:17.919 --> 00:44:20.760
when things go wrong in Shiny, you kind of get that,

00:44:20.760 --> 00:44:23.399
what is it, the skull or the sad loading screen.

00:44:23.399 --> 00:44:25.199
Things are super broken.

00:44:25.199 --> 00:44:28.360
Things are not going well.

00:44:28.360 --> 00:44:30.120
And you get this loud error, and you know

00:44:30.120 --> 00:44:32.120
things are not going well.

00:44:32.120 --> 00:44:33.639
Models don't work like that.

00:44:33.639 --> 00:44:36.000
Models will fail silently, and they can still

00:44:36.000 --> 00:44:38.239
run even if there's no error.

00:44:38.239 --> 00:44:40.760
Even if the accuracy is 0%, your model

00:44:40.760 --> 00:44:42.600
will still give you an output.

00:44:42.600 --> 00:44:45.520
This is something we also see with chat GPT,

00:44:45.520 --> 00:44:46.959
where it'll hallucinate.

00:44:46.959 --> 00:44:47.919
You can ask it things.

00:44:47.919 --> 00:44:51.879
It'll tell you the wrong thing very confidently.

00:44:51.879 --> 00:44:53.399
And that's where monitoring comes in,

00:44:53.399 --> 00:44:57.600
because if you aren't tracking how your model is performing,

00:44:57.600 --> 00:45:01.760
you are oblivious if your model is decaying.

00:45:01.760 --> 00:45:03.479
So it's really important, whether it's

00:45:03.479 --> 00:45:05.919
in some sort of large system or something

00:45:05.919 --> 00:45:08.159
you're doing ad hoc on your own, to do

00:45:08.159 --> 00:45:10.439
some sort of model monitoring.

00:45:13.239 --> 00:45:15.159
And that will complete our cycle.

00:45:15.159 --> 00:45:17.479
You have your model versioned as you're

00:45:17.479 --> 00:45:23.159
creating different experiments, as you're updating your model.

00:45:23.159 --> 00:45:24.879
You can deploy your model.

00:45:24.879 --> 00:45:26.679
You can monitor your model.

00:45:26.679 --> 00:45:29.600
And we can think about this kind of over a long span of time.

00:45:29.600 --> 00:45:35.520
Let's say last year, I created a model, and I deployed it.

00:45:35.520 --> 00:45:37.399
I have my version locally.

00:45:37.399 --> 00:45:39.719
And maybe over the last year, I've been monitoring it,

00:45:39.719 --> 00:45:42.360
and I realize now I need to update my model.

00:45:42.360 --> 00:45:45.239
And retrain it with the new data we've collected.

00:45:45.239 --> 00:45:47.760
Then I can create a new version of that model.

00:45:47.760 --> 00:45:50.760
I get to redeploy it and continue monitoring it

00:45:50.760 --> 00:45:55.800
so this cycle can go on and on.

00:45:55.800 --> 00:45:59.120
So things that are interesting about Veniver that I think

00:45:59.120 --> 00:46:01.439
is something that we should be excited about

00:46:01.439 --> 00:46:03.239
is it's very composable.

00:46:03.239 --> 00:46:07.199
So internally with Veniver API and Veniver model,

00:46:07.199 --> 00:46:11.199
Veniver APIs are just plumber APIs.

00:46:11.239 --> 00:46:14.399
So if you're someone who is a plumber expert

00:46:14.399 --> 00:46:16.600
and wants to add in new endpoints,

00:46:16.600 --> 00:46:22.360
who wants to add in whatever other infrastructure you want

00:46:22.360 --> 00:46:24.239
around this plumber endpoint, you

00:46:24.239 --> 00:46:29.800
can add that into your Veniver API just as you'd expect.

00:46:29.800 --> 00:46:31.199
It's also something that is built

00:46:31.199 --> 00:46:34.120
to be kind of an extension of a data science workflow.

00:46:34.120 --> 00:46:40.439
So you don't have to change the types of models you're creating

00:46:40.439 --> 00:46:41.479
or anything like that.

00:46:41.479 --> 00:46:43.120
It is truly just something to add on,

00:46:43.120 --> 00:46:46.479
not to try to change what you're already doing.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:51.320
Finally, it works with the tools you like.

00:46:51.320 --> 00:46:54.040
This is kind of along the same lines of those ergonomics.

00:46:54.040 --> 00:46:56.639
It should be an extension of what

00:46:56.639 --> 00:47:01.040
is already happening in your data science workflow.

